(381, 1, '2016-01-29 18:29:28', '2016-01-29 18:29:28', '<span style="font-weight: 400;">It’s all over the news!</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Daniel G. Anderson, an MIT researcher, has led a team of experts from MIT, Harvard, and a group of other notable institutions one step farther down the road toward a cure for Type 1 diabetes.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Type 1 diabetes attacks the pancreatic beta cells that produce insulin. The research team has known how produce these cells since 2014, but the recent announcement in journal </span><a href="http://www.nature.com/articles/nm.4030.epdf?referrer_access_token=DbIPD2ZUz4oYStbvOmFmqdRgN0jAjWel9jnR3ZoTv0PUY_rsSYefXVoC8XWheGQJ_zqgkMzX2Wyu-p7xyLN4OZkPQwKstmHyaLGA6WS9O1bxhExDKimgrTK2lDqFtEK9UX_knnpSepby7f14m8bigelQieChePjOfchNQK7U2XjUh7PGqDqLN_3NDdIa2v18cIrQx3OMxWhQfs4cwbjrEdnwcUePEVvfg3F3aFGLglCDZu01btVSUnla0HOzjT_96xJN30M6VunSKqgqAZ52rCdx6_RcvYTcAebjNY-x0zLsWTvKu-1K3QaM37Gn-fmo&amp;tracking_referrer=www.telegraph.co.uk"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Nature</span></i></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> describes how they prevented these implanted cells from provoking an immune response.<a href="http://peersupportsolutions.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/2016-01-27-Diabetes-Type-1-Nature-Cover.gif" rel="attachment wp-att-380"><img class="size-full wp-image-380 alignright" src="http://peersupportsolutions.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/2016-01-27-Diabetes-Type-1-Nature-Cover.gif" alt="2016 01 27 Diabetes Type 1 Nature Cover" width="440" height="580" /></a> </span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">One significant breakthrough was an algae-based coating for the implanted cells, which apparently allowed them to fend off the body’s attacks. The beta cells, thus shielded, were able to produce insulin for the entire 174-day study period without the need for daily insulin injections. If the treatment is eventually approved it’s likely to require only a booster injection of beta cells every few years.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">This is great news for Type 1 sufferers, and a few Type 2 sufferers who may benefit if they eventually come to require injectable insulin. But until there’s a similar breakthrough for Type 2 patients we’ll have to continue with currently available treatments, </span><a href="http://peersupportsolutions.com/our-solutions-2/diabetes/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">including peer support</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Oh - the article’s title? </span><b><i>Long-term glycemic control using polymer-encapsulated human stem cell–derived beta cells in immune-competent mice.</i></b>', 'A Cure for Diabetes…', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '379-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-29 18:29:28', '2016-01-29 18:29:28', '', 379, 'http://peersupportsolutions.com/379-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
